    "pathophysiology": "IgM autoantibodies (cold agglutinins) bind to RBC surface antigens with optimal activity at low temperatures (4-18°C). Upon rewarming in the central circulation, the IgM dissociates but leaves behind C3b deposited on RBCs. C3b-coated RBCs undergo clearance by hepatic macrophages (extravascular hemolysis via CR1 receptors). In severe cases, complement proceeds to membrane attack complex formation causing direct intravascular hemolysis. Cold exposure precipitates RBC agglutination in peripheral microvasculature causing acrocyanosis.",
